  node [
    id 3
    label "3"
    text " okay, so this is something I&#8217;ve been thinking about for years&#10;now&#8212;especially how early exposure, multimodal input, and interaction shape the trajectory&#10;of a child&#8217;s linguistic development"
  ]
  node [
    id 4
    label "4"
    text " In my lab, we study both monolingual and bilingual&#10;children, and what&#8217;s fascinating is how flexible yet rule-governed their acquisition&#10;pathways are"
  ]
  node [
    id 5
    label "5"
    text "  A lot of people ask, &#34;Is it all innate?&#34; Well, yes and no"
  ]
  node [
    id 6
    label "6"
    text " The brain&#10;clearly comes prepared to deal with language, but the input matters immensely"
  ]
  node [
    id 7
    label "7"
    text " We&#8217;ve done&#10;longitudinal studies where children in high-quantity input environments&#8212;lots of adult&#10;speech, child-directed speech, joint attention&#8212;reach syntactic milestones months earlier&#10;than kids in lower input settings"
  ]
  node [
    id 8
    label "8"
    text " It's not just quantity though; quality matters"
  ]
  node [
    id 9
    label "9"
    text " Diverse&#10;vocabulary, varied syntactic frames, pragmatic scaffolding&#8212;those things accelerate&#10;acquisition"
  ]
  node [
    id 10
    label "10"
    text "  And critical periods are real, but maybe not as sharp-edged as we thought"
  ]
  node [
    id 11
    label "11"
    text "&#10;Phonological learning does seem to peak early&#8212;say, before age 2&#8212;but morphosyntactic&#10;learning shows plasticity into adolescence"
  ]
  node [
    id 12
    label "12"
    text " Still, we see a marked drop-off in ultimate&#10;attainment, especially in accent and function word mastery, past certain windows"
  ]
  node [
    id 13
    label "13"
    text "  There&#8217;s&#10;also this ongoing debate between generativist and usage-based models"
  ]
  node [
    id 14
    label "14"
    text " I find myself&#10;somewhere in between"
  ]
  node [
    id 15
    label "15"
    text " I think kids extract rules, yes, but I think those rules are&#10;probabilistic and driven by input frequency"
  ]
  node [
    id 16
    label "16"
    text " Like, they&#8217;re mini Bayesian learners&#8212;tracking&#10;co-occurrence patterns, adjusting hypotheses, revising over time"
  ]
  node [
    id 17
    label "17"
    text "  We&#8217;ve been&#10;incorporating eye-tracking and EEG into our work now"
  ]
  node [
    id 18
    label "18"
    text " With EEG, we can detect ERP&#10;components like the N400 and P600 during sentence processing, even in toddlers"
  ]
  node [
    id 19
    label "19"
    text " That gives&#10;us real-time insight into whether they're treating certain constructions as grammatical or&#10;anomalous"
  ]
  node [
    id 20
    label "20"
    text " Honestly, the data has really pushed us to rethink what counts as&#10;&#8220;understanding"
  ]
  node [
    id 21
    label "21"
    text "&#8221;  And lately, we&#8217;ve been working with L2 learners too&#8212;especially heritage&#10;speakers"
  ]
  node [
    id 22
    label "22"
    text " That&#8217;s a whole different set of variables: identity, literacy, code-switching&#10;norms, and community support"
  ]
  node [
    id 23
    label "23"
    text " But it's all language learning, and it&#8217;s all telling us&#10;something about how flexible and constrained the system is"
  ]
  node [
    id 24
    label "24"
    text "  It&#8217;s a rich field"
  ]
  node [
    id 25
    label "25"
    text " You&#8217;ve got&#10;behavioral experiments, corpus studies, computational modeling&#8212;it&#8217;s a multi-method&#10;ecosystem"
  ]
  node [
    id 26
    label "26"
    text " No single approach will explain everything"
  ]
  node [
    id 27
    label "27"
    text " But what I love most is that&#10;language acquisition research is always, at its heart, about people learning to connect&#10;with one another"
  ]
